    "long_instructions": "##### **Teacher Note**: This is Lesson 12, level 7 from the curriculum.\r\n___\r\n\r\n### Remix\r\n\r\nOne final way to explore remixes is to play with timing. Most of the time, tracks start-and-end on predictable measures. You can used rests strategically to create new patterns, where some tracks start on top of each other and create entirely new sounds. Let's try that with this remix of I Need a Dollar by Aloe Blacc\r\n\r\n**Do This:**\r\n- Experiment with adding new tracks to the `remix` function. You can add `play together` blocks and `play` tracks inside the `play sequential` blocks. - [<i class=\"fa-solid fa-lightbulb\"></i> <i class=\"fa-solid fa-square-right\"></i>](#clickable=flyout-id:play_toolbox---id-up-inside:play_sequential_workspace)\r\n- Try using the same track in multiple places so it overlaps and see how it sounds\r\n\r\nYou can pass this level when you've played at least 3 new tracks to your song and one of them plays at least 2 times (so it overlaps). Here's an example of how your timeline might look:\r\n\r\n![](https://images.code.org/17a87996e6d9d1c09391e685e8991da4-image-1745963165545.png)",
